27 BEACH AND INLET MANAGEMENT PLAN AND REPORT
28 SECTION 5.7.(a) Article 21 of Chapter 143 of the General Statutes is amended by
29 adding a new Part 8E, to be entitled "Beach and Inlet Management Planning." Section 4.9 of S.L.
30 2017-10 is repealed. Section 13.9 of S.L. 2000-67 is codified within Part 8E, as follows:
31 (1) Section 13.9(a) is codified as G.S. 143-215.73N, to be entitled "Findings."
32 (2) Sections 13.9(b), 13.9(c), and 13.9(d) are codified as subsections (a), (b), and
33 (c) of G.S. 143-215.73O, to be entitled "Beach and inlet management plan."
34 (3) Section 13.9(e) is repealed.
35 (4) Section 13.9(f) is codified as G.S. 143-215.73P, to be entitled "Federal funds;
36 matching."
37 SECTION 5.7.(b) Part 8E of Article 21 of Chapter 143 of the General Statutes, as
38 enacted by subsection (a) of this section, reads as rewritten:
39 "Part 8E. Beach and Inlet Management Planning.
40 "§ 143-215.73N. Findings.
41 The General Assembly makes the following findings:
42 (1) North Carolina has 320 miles of ocean beach, including some of the most
43 pristine and attractive beaches in the country.
44 (2) The balance between economic development and quality of life in North
45 Carolina has made our coast one of the most desirable along the Atlantic
46 Seaboard.
47 (3) North Carolina's beaches are vital to the State's tourism industry.
48 (4) North Carolina's beaches belong to all the State's citizens and provide
49 recreational and economic benefits to our residents statewide.
50 (5) Beach erosion can threaten the economic viability of coastal communities and
51 can significantly affect State tax revenues.
Page 12 House Bill 125-Third Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (6) The Atlantic Seaboard is vulnerable to hurricanes and other coastal storms,
2 and it is prudent to take precautions such as beach nourishment that protect
3 and conserve the State's beaches and reduce property damage and flooding.
4 (7) Beach renourishment as an erosion control method provides hurricane flood
5 protection, enhances the attractiveness of beaches to tourists, restores habitat
6 for turtles, shorebirds, and plants, and provides additional public access to
7 beaches.
8 (8) Federal policy previously favored and assisted voluntary movement of
9 structures threatened by erosion, but this assistance is no longer available.
10 (9) Relocation of structures threatened by erosion is sometimes the best available
11 remedy for the property owner and is in the public interest.
12 (10) Public parking and public access areas are needed for use by the general public
13 to enable their enjoyment of North Carolina's beaches.
14 (11) Acquisition of high erosion hazard property by local or State agencies can
15 reduce risk to citizens and property, reduce costs to insurance policyholders,
16 improve public access to beaches and waterways, and protect the
17 environment.
18 (12) Beach nourishment projects such as those at Wrightsville Beach and Carolina
19 Beach have been very successful and greatly reduced property damage during
20 Hurricane Fran.hurricanes and other coastal storms that have impacted the
21 State's coast.
22 (13) Because local beach communities derive the primary benefits from the
23 presence of adequate beaches, a program of beach management and
24 restoration should not be accomplished without a commitment of local funds
25 to combat the problem of beach erosion.
26 (14) The With limited exceptions, the State of North Carolina prohibits seawalls
27 and hardening the shoreline to prevent destroying the public's beaches.
28 (15) Beach nourishment is encouraged by both the Coastal Resources Commission
29 and the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers as a method to control beach erosion.
30 (16) The Department of Environment and Natural Resources Environmental
31 Quality has statutory authority to assist local governments in financing beach
32 nourishment projects and is the sponsor of several federal navigation projects
33 that result in dredging beach-quality sand.
34 (17) It is declared to be a necessary governmental responsibility to properly
35 manage and protect North Carolina's beaches from erosion and that good
36 planning is needed to assure a cost-effective and equitable approach to beach
37 management and restoration, and that as part of a comprehensive response to
38 beach erosion, sound policies are needed to facilitate the ability of landowners
39 to move threatened structures and to allow public acquisition of appropriate
40 parcels of land for public beach access.
41 "§ 143-215.73O. Beach and inlet management plan.
42 (a) The Department of Environment and Natural Resources Environmental Quality shall
43 compile and evaluate information on the current conditions and erosion rates of beaches, on
44 coastal geology, and on storm and erosion hazards for use in developing a State plan and strategy
45 for beach management and restoration. The Department of Environment and Natural Resources
46 Environmental Quality shall make this information available to local governments for use in
47 land-use planning.
48 (b) The Department of Environment and Natural Resources Environmental Quality shall
49 develop a multiyear beach management and restoration strategy and plan that does all of the
50 following:
House Bill 125-Third Edition Page 13

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) Utilizes the data and expertise available in the Divisions of Water Resources,
2 Coastal Management, and Energy, Mineral, and Land Resources.
3 (2) Identifies the erosion rate at each beach community and estimates the degree
4 of vulnerability to storm and hurricane damage.
5 (3) Uses the best available geological and geographical information to determine
6 the need for and probable effectiveness of beach nourishment.
7 (4) Provides for coordination with the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, the North
8 Carolina Department of Transportation, the North Carolina Division of
9 Emergency Management, and other State and federal agencies concerned with
10 beach management issues.
11 (5) Provides a status report on all U.S. Army Corps of Engineers' beach protection
12 projects in the planning, construction, or operational stages.
13 (6) Makes maximum feasible use of suitable sand dredged from navigation
14 channels for beach nourishment to avoid the loss of this resource and to reduce
15 equipment mobilization costs.
16 (7) Promotes inlet sand bypassing where needed to replicate the natural flow of
17 sand interrupted by inlets.
18 (8) Provides for geological and environmental assessments to locate suitable
19 materials for beach nourishment.
20 (9) Considers the regional context of beach communities to determine the most
21 cost-effective approach to beach nourishment.
22 (10) Provides for and requires adequate public beach access, including
23 handicapped access.
24 (11) Recommends priorities for State funding for beach nourishment projects,
25 based on the amount of erosion occurring, the potential damage to property
26 and to the economy, the benefits for recreation and tourism, the adequacy of
27 public access, the availability of local government matching funds, the status
28 of project planning, the adequacy of project engineering, the
29 cost-effectiveness of the project, and the environmental impacts.
30 (12) Includes a four-year cycle of planned maintenance and resiliency projects for
31 the State's beaches and inlets.
32 (12)(13) Includes recommendations on obtaining the maximum available federal
33 financial assistance for beach nourishment.
34 (13)(14) Is subject to a public hearing to receive citizen input.
35 (c) Each plan shall be as complete as resources and available information allow. The
36 Department of Environment and Natural Resources Environmental Quality shall revise the plan
37 every two years and shall submit the revised plan to the General Assembly no later than March
38 1 of each odd-numbered year. The Department may issue a supplement to the plan in
39 even-numbered years if significant new information becomes available.
40 "§ 143-215.73P. Federal funds; matching.
41 In the event that federal funds become available for planning and developing shore protection
42 projects, the State shall match those funds in accordance with the funding guidelines set out in
43 G.S. 143-215.71."
