31 SCHOOL SAFETY GRANTS
32 SECTION 6.4.(a) Definitions. – For the purposes of this section, the following
33 definitions shall apply:
34 (1) Community partner. – A public or private entity, including, but not limited to,
35 a nonprofit corporation or a local management entity/managed care
36 organization (LME/MCO), that partners with a public school unit to provide
37 services or pay for the provision of services for the unit.
38 (2) School health support personnel. – School psychologists, school counselors,
39 school nurses, and school social workers.
40 SECTION 6.4.(b) Program; Purpose. – The Executive Director of the Center for
41 Safer Schools shall establish the School Safety Grants Program (Program) for the 2025-2027
42 fiscal biennium. The purpose of the Program shall be to improve safety in public school units by
43 providing grants in each fiscal year of the 2025-2027 fiscal biennium for (i) services for students
44 in crisis, (ii) school safety training, (iii) safety equipment in schools, and (iv) subsidizing the
45 School Resource Officer Grants Program.
46 SECTION 6.4.(c) Grant Applications. – A public school unit may submit an
47 application to the Executive Director of the Center for Safer Schools for one or more grants
48 pursuant to this section in each year of the 2025-2027 fiscal biennium. The application shall
49 include an assessment, to be performed in conjunction with a local law enforcement agency, of
50 the need for improving school safety within the public school unit that would receive the funding
Page 18 House Bill 125-Third Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 or services. The application shall identify current and ongoing needs and estimated costs
2 associated with those needs.
3 SECTION 6.4.(d) Criteria and Guidelines. – The Executive Director of the Center
4 for Safer Schools shall develop criteria and guidelines for the administration and use of the grants
5 pursuant to this section, including any documentation required to be submitted by applicants. In
6 assessing grant applications, the Executive Director shall consider at least all of the following
7 factors:
8 (1) The level of resources available to the public school unit that would receive
9 the funding.
10 (2) Whether the public school unit has received other grants for school safety.
11 (3) The overall impact on student safety in the public school unit if the identified
12 needs are funded.
13 SECTION 6.4.(e) Grants for Students in Crisis. – Of the funds appropriated by this
14 section for the grants provided in this section, the Executive Director of the Center for Safer
15 Schools, in consultation with the Department of Health and Human Services, shall award grants
16 to public school units to contract with community partners to provide or pay for the provision of
17 any of the following crisis services:
18 (1) Crisis respite services for parents or guardians of an individual student to
19 prevent more intensive or costly levels of care.
20 (2) Training and expanded services for therapeutic foster care families and
21 licensed child placement agencies that provide services to students who (i)
22 need support to manage their health, welfare, and safety and (ii) have any of
23 the following:
24 a. Cognitive or behavioral problems.
25 b. Developmental delays.
26 c. Aggressive behavior.
27 (3) Evidence-based therapy services aligned with targeted training for students
28 and their parents or guardians, including any of the following:
29 a. Parent-child interaction therapy.
30 b. Trauma-focused cognitive behavioral therapy.
31 c. Dialectical behavior therapy.
32 d. Child-parent psychotherapy.
33 (4) Any other crisis service, including peer-to-peer mentoring, that is likely to
34 increase school safety. Of the funds appropriated by this act for the grants
35 provided in this section, the Executive Director shall use no more than three
36 hundred fifty thousand dollars ($350,000) in each fiscal year of the 2025-2027
37 fiscal biennium for the services identified in this subdivision.
38 SECTION 6.4.(f) Grants for Training to Increase School Safety. – Of the funds
39 appropriated by this section for the grants provided in this section, the Executive Director of the
40 Center for Safer Schools, in consultation with the Department of Health and Human Services,
41 shall award grants to public school units to contract with community partners to address school
42 safety by providing training to help students develop healthy responses to trauma and stress. The
43 training shall be targeted and evidence-based and shall include any of the following services:
44 (1) Counseling on Access to Lethal Means (CALM) training for school health
45 support personnel, local first responders, and teachers on the topics of suicide
46 prevention and reducing access by students to lethal means.
47 (2) Training for school health support personnel on comprehensive and
48 evidence-based clinical treatments for students and their parents or guardians,
49 including any of the following:
50 a. Parent-child interaction therapy.
51 b. Trauma-focused cognitive behavioral therapy.
House Bill 125-Third Edition Page 19

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 c. Behavioral therapy.
2 d. Dialectical behavior therapy.
3 e. Child-parent psychotherapy.
4 (3) Training for students and school employees on community resilience models
5 to improve understanding and responses to trauma and significant stress.
6 (4) Training for school health support personnel on Modular Approach to
7 Therapy for Children with Anxiety, Depression, Trauma, or Conduct
8 problems (MATCH-ADTC), including any of the following components:
9 a. Trauma-focused cognitive behavioral therapy.
10 b. Parent and student coping skills.
11 c. Problem solving.
12 d. Safety planning.
13 (5) Any other training, including the training on the facilitation of peer-to-peer
14 mentoring, that is likely to increase school safety. Of the funds appropriated
15 by this section for the grants provided in this section, the Executive Director
16 shall use no more than three hundred fifty thousand dollars ($350,000) in each
17 fiscal year of the 2025-2027 fiscal biennium for the services identified in this
18 subdivision.
19 SECTION 6.4.(g) Grants for Safety Equipment. – Of the funds appropriated by this
20 section for the grants provided in this section, the Executive Director of the Center for Safer
21 Schools shall award grants to public school units for (i) the purchase of safety equipment for
22 school buildings and (ii) training associated with the use of safety equipment purchased pursuant
23 to this subsection. Notwithstanding G.S. 115C-218.105(b), charter schools may receive grants
24 for school safety equipment pursuant to this subsection.
25 SECTION 6.4.(h) Subsidizing School Resource Officer Grants Program. – If the
26 Executive Director of the Center for Safer Schools receives applications for grants for school
27 resource officers under G.S. 143B-1208.20 in excess of the amount of funding appropriated for
28 school resource officer grants in the 2025-2027 fiscal biennium, the Executive Director may use
29 the funds appropriated for the grants provided for in this section to cover the unmet need for
30 school resource officer grants.
31 SECTION 6.4.(i) Supplement Not Supplant. – Grants provided to public school units
32 pursuant to the Program shall be used to supplement and not to supplant State or non-State funds
33 already provided for these services.
34 SECTION 6.4.(j) Administrative Costs. – Of the funds appropriated to the Center
35 for Safer Schools by this section for the grants provided in this section, the Executive Director
36 of the Center for Safer Schools may retain a total of up to one hundred thousand dollars
37 ($100,000) in each fiscal year of the 2025-2027 fiscal biennium for administrative costs
38 associated with the Program.
39 SECTION 6.4.(k) Disbursement. – The Executive Director of the Center for Safer
40 Schools may enter into a memorandum of understanding with the Department of Public
41 Instruction to disburse grants awarded under this section.
42 SECTION 6.4.(l) Program Report. – No later than April 1 of each fiscal year in
43 which funds are awarded pursuant to this section, the Executive Director of the Center for Safer
44 Schools shall report on the Program to the Joint Legislative Education Oversight Committee, the
45 Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on Health and Human Services, the Joint Legislative
46 Oversight Committee on Justice and Public Safety, the Joint Legislative Commission on
47 Governmental Operations, the Senate Appropriations/Base Budget Committee, the House
48 Committee on Appropriations, and the Fiscal Research Division. The report shall include at least
49 the following information:
50 (1) The identity of each public school unit and community partner that received
51 grant funds through the Program.
