28 "SECTION 14.10.(b) Membership. – The Committee shall be composed of seven nine
29 members, as follows:
30 (1) Three Four members appointed by the President Pro Tempore of the Senate,
31 one two of whom shall be a member members of the Senate and the remainder
32 of whom shall be members of the public.
33 (2) Three Four members appointed by the Speaker of the House of
34 Representatives, one two of whom shall be a member members of the House
35 of Representatives and the remainder of whom shall be members of the public.
36 (3) One member jointly appointed by the President Pro Tempore of the Senate
37 and the Speaker of the House of Representatives who shall be a noted historian
38 with expertise regarding the American Revolution.
39 "SECTION 14.10.(c) Terms; Chairs; Vacancies; Quorum. – Members appointed shall serve
40 until the Committee terminates. The Committee shall have two cochairs which shall be the
41 legislative member designated by the President Pro Tempore of the Senate and the legislative
42 member designated by the Speaker of the House of Representatives. The Committee shall meet
43 upon the call of the cochairs. Vacancies shall be filled by the appointing authority. A quorum of
44 the Committee shall be a majority of the members.
45 "SECTION 14.10.(d) Duties. – The Committee shall (i) study means for the State to
46 celebrate the two hundred fiftieth anniversary of the founding of our nation and (ii) report the
47 means and anticipated costs of the celebratory events to the General Assembly.The Committee
48 shall do the following:
49 (1) Establish a website, social media, and distribution list to provide:
50 a. Visual, auditory, or written informational resources about the history
51 of the semiquincentennial and North Carolina's role in the founding of
House Bill 125-Third Edition Page 29

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 the United States, including materials that can be used in educational
2 settings.
3 b. A clearinghouse of activities to recognize, celebrate, and
4 commemorate the semiquincentennial occurring at the State and local
5 level.
6 c. Suggestions of how citizens of the State can recognize, celebrate, and
7 commemorate the semiquincentennial.
8 (2) Advise the North Carolina Symphony and other symphonies and choral
9 groups, the University of North Carolina Center for Public Media, and
10 interested nonprofits throughout the State on historically relevant information
11 to assist in the development of programming with semiquincentennial themes.
12 (3) Facilitate connections between State agencies, local governments,
13 semiquincentennial committees at the federal, State, or local level, educational
14 institutions, nonprofits, historical, cultural, and business entities, and
15 hereditary organizations for the purpose of coordinating events and activities
16 that recognize, celebrate, and commemorate the semiquincentennial.
17 (4) Identify historians and other individuals with expertise on events related to the
18 semiquincentennial who can serve as resources and speakers for
19 semiquincentennial events, including members of the Committee.
20 (5) Identify, encourage, facilitate, and publicize any other means of recognition,
21 celebration, and commemoration of the semiquincentennial that the
